comments.body:
I also encountered the same issue where I believe that two cells were using a shared style. My situation is as follows: I uploaded an xlsx file, parsed it using exceljs, set the background color for a specific cell, and then exported it. However, I noticed that many other cells also had their colors changed.
![60cfc50629a0d2ab553a86a3810284c2](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/assets/58138234/4d4a54c5-f773-40db-88c9-1349a4c0d736)

To address this issue, I suggest clearing the original styles before adding styles to the cells. The following code snippet may help you achieve that:
```ts
worksheet.eachRow({  includeEmpty: true }, (row) => {
    row.eachCell({ includeEmpty: true  }, (cell) => {
        cell.style = {};
     });
 });
```
But I still hope to provide an attribute to indicate that I want to set the styles of certain cells independently, instead of applying the styles to a group of cells. Additionally, it would be helpful to have a utility function, such as `worksheet.clearStyle("A1:B5")`, that allows me to remove the style association between specific cells.
